<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="199" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="199">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="199">The specific name is a patronym in honour of Prof. Xianjin Peng (College of Life Sciences, Hunan Normal University), one of the leading spider taxonomists of China; noun (name) in genitive case.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="199" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="199">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="199">
This new species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. yunnanensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="199" rank="species" species="yunnanensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">E. yunnanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in appearance, but can be distinguished from the latter by: 1) having a thread-like terminal apophysis vs. not thread-like (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Eriovixia yunnanensis A male palp, dorsal view B ibid., prolateral view C male habitus, dorsal view D ibid., lateral view E female habitus, dorsal view F ibid., ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, B); 1 mm (C-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535316" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">13A, B</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Male palps of Eriovixia spp, apical view A E. yaoi sp. nov. B E. yinae sp. nov. C E. yunnanensis D E. zhengi sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535321" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">18C</figureCitation>
); 2) the straight and pointed embolus vs. curved and non-tapering embolus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Eriovixia yunnanensis A male palp, dorsal view B ibid., prolateral view C male habitus, dorsal view D ibid., lateral view E female habitus, dorsal view F ibid., ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, B); 1 mm (C-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535316" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">13A</figureCitation>
); 3) the branches of the median apophysis about 45° apart vs. very close to each other (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Eriovixia yunnanensis A male palp, dorsal view B ibid., prolateral view C male habitus, dorsal view D ibid., lateral view E female habitus, dorsal view F ibid., ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, B); 1 mm (C-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535316" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">13A, B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Male palps of Eriovixia spp, apical view A E. yaoi sp. nov. B E. yinae sp. nov. C E. yunnanensis D E. zhengi sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535321" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">18C</figureCitation>
); 4) a pair of rhomboidal copulatory openings vs. arcuate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Eriovixia yunnanensis, epigyne A ventral view B dorsal view C lateral view D dorsal view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535317" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">14B, D</figureCitation>
). It is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. yaoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="199" rank="species" species="yaoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">E. yaoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. by the copulatory organs and the habitus, but differs in having: 1) a thread-like terminal apophysis vs. bifurcated (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Eriovixia yaoi sp. nov., male holotype and female paratype A male palp, dorsal view B ibid., prolateral view C holotype habitus, dorsal view D ibid., lateral view E paratype habitus, dorsal view F ibid., ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, B); 1 mm (C-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535312" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">9A, B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Male palps of Eriovixia spp, apical view A E. yaoi sp. nov. B E. yinae sp. nov. C E. yunnanensis D E. zhengi sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535321" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">18A</figureCitation>
); 2) straight embolus vs. curved (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Eriovixia yaoi sp. nov., male holotype and female paratype A male palp, dorsal view B ibid., prolateral view C holotype habitus, dorsal view D ibid., lateral view E paratype habitus, dorsal view F ibid., ventral view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm (A, B); 1 mm (C-F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535312" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">9A</figureCitation>
); and 3) a pair of rhomboidal copulatory openings vs. arcuate (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Eriovixia yaoi sp. nov., female paratype, epigyne A ventral view B dorsal view C lateral view D dorsal view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1034.60411.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/535313" pageId="0" pageNumber="199">10B, D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
